            "answer_text": "He said it, possibly, in 1940, but he didn\u2019t originated it. People aren\u2019t sure who did. One scholar found it in a book from 1934, though he didn\u2019t list the title. The phrase has been used often, and the sentiment has been used even more so. In the movie \u2018Operation Petticoat\u2019 an American Submarine base in the Philippines is being bombed in December \u201841. The crew of a submarine is trying to repair their boat and get out, but the bureaucracy, even in desperate wartime, is hindering them. During the air raid, an officer declares \"In confusion there is profit\u201d and proceeded to procure (steal) what they need including a badly needed supply of toilet paper. The sentiment is simple, in times of crisis, chaos, or air raids, there is an opportunity for great leaders to rise to the occasion in ways that they couldn\u2019t in times of normal. And there\u2019s the opportunity for jabbering mental patients to kill 100,000 people because they are out of their depth. ",
